               <jats:sub>
                  <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>
               </jats:sub> (<jats:italic>M</jats:italic>) of complete <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>-types over <jats:italic>M</jats:italic> is an inverse limit of some semigroups type-definable in <jats:italic>M</jats:italic>
               <jats:sup>
                  <jats:italic>eq</jats:italic>
               </jats:sup>. We prove that the maximal subgroups of <jats:italic>S</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>
                  <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>
               </jats:sub> (<jats:italic>M</jats:italic>) are inverse limits of some definable quotients of subgroups of <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>. We consider the powers of types in the semigroup <jats:italic>S</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>
                  <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>
               </jats:sub> (<jats:italic>M</jats:italic>) and prove that in a way every type in <jats:italic>S</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>
                  <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>
               </jats:sub> (<jats:italic>M</jats:italic>) is profinitely many steps away from a type in a subgroup of <jats:italic>S</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>
                  <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>
               </jats:sub> (<jats:italic>M</jats:italic>).</jats:p>

<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
            <jats:p>We consider a small supersimple theory with a property (CS) (close to stability). We prove that if in such a theory <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> there is a type <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> ∈ <jats:italic>S</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>A</jats:italic>) (where <jats:italic>A</jats:italic> is finite) with <jats:italic>SU</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>p</jats:italic>) = 1 and infinitely many extensions over <jats:italic>acl<jats:sup>eq</jats:sup>
               </jats:italic>(<jats:italic>A</jats:italic>), then in <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> there is a modular such type. Also, if <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> is supersimple with (CS) and <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> ∈ <jats:italic>S</jats:italic>(∅) is isolated, <jats:italic>SU</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>p</jats:italic>) = 1 and <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> has infinitely many extensions over <jats:italic>acl<jats:sup>eq</jats:sup>
               </jats:italic> (∅), then <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> is modular.</jats:p>
title: Modular types in some supersimple theories

<jats:p>The problem mentioned in the title has already been investigated by J. Baumgartner, J. Stern, A. Miller and many others (see [2] and [5]). We prove here some generalizations of theorems of Miller and Stern from [2] and [5]. We use standard set-theoretical notation. Let</jats:p>
            <jats:p>
               <jats:disp-formula>
                  <jats:graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" mimetype="image" position="float" xlink:href="S0022481200034307_eqnU1" xlink:type="simple" />
               </jats:disp-formula>
            </jats:p>
            <jats:p>One can check that in the above definition we can replace “compact subset of <jats:italic>
                  <jats:sup>ω</jats:sup>ω”</jats:italic> by “closed nowhere dense subset of <jats:sup>
                  <jats:italic>ω</jats:italic>
               </jats:sup>2” or “<jats:italic>F</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>σ</jats:sub> and meager subset of <jats:sup>
                  <jats:italic>ω</jats:italic>
               </jats:sup>2” (as any <jats:italic>F</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>
                  <jats:italic>σ</jats:italic>
               </jats:sub> subset of <jats:sup>
                  <jats:italic>ω</jats:italic>
               </jats:sup>2 can be presented as a disjoint countable union of compact sets).</jats:p>
            <jats:p>For functions <jats:italic>f, g</jats:italic> ϵ <jats:italic>
                  <jats:sup>ω</jats:sup>ω</jats:italic> we define <jats:italic>f</jats:italic> ≼ <jats:italic>g</jats:italic> if for all but finitely many <jats:italic>n</jats:italic> ϵ <jats:italic>ω</jats:italic> we have <jats:italic>f(n)</jats:italic> ≤ <jats:italic>g(n)</jats:italic>. Let <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200034307_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> denote the least cardinality of a family <jats:italic>A</jats:italic> ⊆ <jats:italic>
                  <jats:sup>ω</jats:sup>ω</jats:italic> such that for any <jats:italic>f</jats:italic> ϵ <jats:italic>
                  <jats:sup>ω</jats:sup>ω</jats:italic> there is <jats:italic>g</jats:italic> ϵ <jats:italic>A</jats:italic> for which <jats:italic>f</jats:italic> ≼ <jats:italic>g</jats:italic>. It is easy to see that <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200034307_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> ≤ <jats:italic>κ<jats:sub>ω</jats:sub>
               </jats:italic> ≤ <jats:italic>κ</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>1</jats:sub>. If <jats:italic>f</jats:italic> ϵ <jats:italic>
                  <jats:sup>ω</jats:sup>ω</jats:italic> then let ≼(<jats:italic>f</jats:italic>) = {<jats:italic>h</jats:italic> ϵ<jats:italic>
                  <jats:sup>ω</jats:sup>ω</jats:italic>: <jats:italic>h</jats:italic> ≼ <jats:italic>f</jats:italic>}.</jats:p>
            <jats:p>We find an axiom which implies <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200034307_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> = <jats:italic>ω</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>1</jats:sub> → <jats:italic>κ</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>1</jats:sub> = <jats:italic>ω</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>1</jats:sub>, and which can be preserved by any ccc notion of forcing of “small cardinality”. We construct also in a generic model many partitions of <jats:italic>
                  <jats:sup>ω</jats:sup>ω</jats:italic> into compact sets preserved not only by any random real extension, but also by Sacks' notion of forcing. This shows that from some point of view Miller's modification of Sacks' forcing (from [2]) is the “minimal” one able to destroy a partition of <jats:italic>
                  <jats:sup>ω</jats:sup>ω</jats:italic> into compact sets.</jats:p>
title: On partitions of the real line into compact sets

items.abstract:
<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
            <jats:p>Assume <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> is a small superstable theory. We introduce the notion of a flat Morley sequence, which is a counterpart of the notion of an infinite Morley sequence in a type <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>, in case when <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> is a complete type over a finite set of parameters. We show that for any flat Morley sequence <jats:italic>Q</jats:italic> there is a model <jats:italic>M</jats:italic> of <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> which is <jats:italic>τ</jats:italic>-atomic over {<jats:italic>Q</jats:italic>}. When additionally <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> has few countable models and is 1-based, we prove that within <jats:italic>M</jats:italic> there is an infinite Morley sequence <jats:italic>I</jats:italic>, with <jats:italic>I</jats:italic>  ⊂ dcl(<jats:italic>Q</jats:italic>), such that <jats:italic>M</jats:italic> is prime over <jats:italic>I</jats:italic>.</jats:p>
title: Flat Morley sequences

items.abstract:
<jats:p>In this paper we investigate omitting types for a certain kind of stable theories which we call stable ccc theories. In Theorem 2.1 we improve Steinhorn's result from [St]. We prove also some independence results concerning omitting types. The main results presented in this paper were part of the author's Ph.D. thesis [N1].</jats:p>
            <jats:p>Throughout, we use the standard set-theoretic and model-theoretic notation, such as can be found for example in [Sh] or [M]. So in particular <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> is always a <jats:italic>countable</jats:italic> complete theory in the language <jats:italic>L</jats:italic>. We consider all models of <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> and all sets of parameters subsets of the monster model ℭ, which is very saturated. <jats:italic>L<jats:sub>n</jats:sub>
               </jats:italic>(<jats:italic>A</jats:italic>) denotes the Lindenbaum-Tarski algebra of formulas with parameters from <jats:italic>A</jats:italic> and <jats:italic>n</jats:italic> free variables. We omit <jats:italic>n</jats:italic> in <jats:italic>L<jats:sub>n</jats:sub>
               </jats:italic>(<jats:italic>A</jats:italic>) when <jats:italic>n</jats:italic> = 1 or when it is clear from the context what <jats:italic>n</jats:italic> is. If <jats:italic>φ, ψ</jats:italic> ∈ <jats:italic>L</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>A</jats:italic>) are consistent then we say that <jats:italic>φ</jats:italic> is <jats:italic>below ψ</jats:italic> if <jats:italic>ψ</jats:italic>⊢<jats:italic>ψ</jats:italic>. For a type <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> and a set <jats:italic>A</jats:italic> ⊆ ℭ, <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>A)</jats:italic> is the set of tuples of elements of <jats:italic>A</jats:italic> which satisfy <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>. Formulas are special cases of types. We say that a type <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> is <jats:italic>isolated</jats:italic> over <jats:italic>A</jats:italic> if, for some <jats:italic>φ(<jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200025548_inline3" xlink:type="simple" />)</jats:italic> ∈ <jats:italic>L(A)</jats:italic>, <jats:italic>φ(<jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200025548_inline3" xlink:type="simple" />)</jats:italic> ⊢ <jats:italic>p(x)</jats:italic>, i.e. <jats:italic>φ</jats:italic> isolates <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>. For a formula <jats:italic>φ</jats:italic>, [<jats:italic>φ</jats:italic>] denotes the class of types which contain <jats:italic>φ</jats:italic>. We assume that the reader is familiar with some basic knowledge of forking, as presented in [Sh, III] or [M].</jats:p>
            <jats:p>Throughout, we work in ZFC. <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200025548_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> and <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200025548_inline2" xlink:type="simple" /> denote (countable) transitive models of ZFC. cov <jats:bold>K</jats:bold> is the minimal number of meager sets covering the real line <jats:bold>R</jats:bold>. In this paper we prove theorems showing connections between omitting types and the combinatorics of the real line. More results in this direction are presented in [N2] and [N3].</jats:p>
title: Omitting types for stable ccc theories

<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
            <jats:p>Assume <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> is stable, small and Φ(<jats:italic>x</jats:italic>) is a formula of <jats:italic>L</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>T</jats:italic>). We study the impact on <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>⌈Φ of naming finitely many elements of a model of <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>. We consider the cases of <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>⌈Φ which is <jats:italic>ω</jats:italic>-stable or superstable of finite rank. In these cases we prove that if <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> has <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200017801_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> countable models and <jats:italic>Q</jats:italic> = Φ(<jats:italic>M</jats:italic>) is countable and atomic or saturated, then any good type in <jats:italic>S</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>Q</jats:italic>) is <jats:italic>τ</jats:italic>-stable. If <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>⌈Φ is <jats:italic>ω</jats:italic>-stable and (bounded, 1-based or of finite rank) with <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200017801_inline2" xlink:type="simple" />, then we prove that every good <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> ∈ <jats:italic>S</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>Q</jats:italic>) is <jats:italic>τ</jats:italic>-stable for any countable <jats:italic>Q</jats:italic>. The proofs of these results lead to several new properties of small stable theories, particularly of types of finite weight in such theories.</jats:p>
title: On atomic or saturated sets

items.abstract:
<jats:p>We investigate some relations between omitting types of a countable theory and some notions defined in terms of the real line, such as for example the ideal of meager subsets of <jats:bold>R</jats:bold>. We also try to express connections between the logical structure of a theory and the existence of its countable models omitting certain families of types.</jats:p>
            <jats:p>It is well known that assuming MA we can omit &lt; <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200029406_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> nonisolated types. But MA is rather a strong axiom. We prove that in order to be able to omit &lt; <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200029406_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> nonisolated types it is sufficient to assume that the real line cannot be covered by less than <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200029406_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> meager sets; and this is in fact the weakest possible condition. It is worth pointing out that by means of forcing we can easily obtain the model of ZFC in which <jats:bold>R</jats:bold> cannot be covered by &lt; <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200029406_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> meager sets. It suffices to add to the ground model <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200029406_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> Cohen generic reals.</jats:p>
            <jats:p>We also formulate similar results for omitting pairwise contradictory types. It turns out that from some point of view it is much more difficult to find the family of pairwise contradictory types which cannot be omitted by a model of <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>, than to find such a family of possibly noncontradictory types. Moreover, for any two countable theories <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>1</jats:sub>, <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>2</jats:sub> without prime models, the existence of a family of <jats:italic>κ</jats:italic> types which cannot be omitted by a model of <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>1</jats:sub> is equivalent to the existence of such a family for <jats:italic>T</jats:italic>
               <jats:sub>2</jats:sub>. This means that from the point of view of omitting types all theories without prime models are identical. Similar results hold for omitting pairwise contradictory types.</jats:p>
title: Omitting types and the real line

items.abstract:
<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
            <jats:p>Assume <jats:italic>T</jats:italic> is a superstable theory with &lt; 2<jats:sup>ℵ<jats:sub>0</jats:sub>
               </jats:sup> countable models. We prove that any *- algebraic type of <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200012627_inline1" xlink:type="simple" />-rank &gt; 0 is m-nonorthogonal to a *-algebraic type of <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200012627_inline3" xlink:type="simple" />-rank 1. We study the geometry induced by m-dependence on a *-algebraic type <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>
               <jats:sup>*</jats:sup> of <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200012627_inline4" xlink:type="simple" />-rank 1. We prove that after some localization this geometry becomes projective over a division ring <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200012627_inline2" xlink:type="simple" />. Associated with <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>
               <jats:sup>*</jats:sup> is a meager type <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>. We prove that <jats:italic>p</jats:italic> is determined by <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>
               <jats:sup>*</jats:sup> up to nonorthogonality and that <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200012627_inline5" xlink:type="simple" /> underlies also the geometry induced by forking dependence on any stationarization of <jats:italic>p</jats:italic>. Also we study some *-algebraic *-groups of <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200012627_inline6" xlink:type="simple" />-rank 1 and prove that any *-algebraic *-group of <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200012627_inline7" xlink:type="simple" />-rank 1 is abelian-by-finite.</jats:p>
title: Geometry of *-Finite Types

items.abstract:
<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
            <jats:p>We propose a model-theoretic framework for investigating profinite groups. Within this framework we define and investigate small profinite groups. We consider the question if any small profinite group has an open abelian subgroup.</jats:p>
title: Small profinite groups
